Why --skip-push instead of --push-pi-wasm: every other step in build.sh is opt-out (runs by default unless --skip-X). My first pass made this opt-in, which would have been the only exception and surprise users who expect the 'do everything' default. User caught it in review. Corrected to match the established pattern.

Why skip gracefully instead of hard-failing: the docker step already handles 'docker not installed' by skipping with a message. Push prerequisites (oras, a reachable registry) aren't standard dev-machine installs, so failing the whole build when they're absent would be user-hostile — especially for contributors who don't care about the harness pipeline and are just running build.sh to compile. Skip with diagnostic, move on.

Why write-bundled-wasm as a CLI subcommand and not a standalone binary or build-time script: the bundled WAT source lives in xpressclaw-core. Reading it from anywhere else would either require duplicating the source (fork-risk) or shelling out to a Rust build. The CLI subcommand is free — one more entry in commands/mod.rs, delegating to HarnessImageResolver's existing materialize_bundled_fallback.

Why OCI artifact with custom media type instead of a plain OCI image: 'oras push' with --artifact-type produces a manifest that calls out 'this is a xpressclaw harness WASM' in one field. Consumers can filter/validate without cracking the blob open. Generic OCI images would leave that discrimination to path conventions (repo names), which is fragile.

Why --plain-http: local registries (podman/docker) don't ship TLS by default. Users aren't going to generate certs for a test registry. oras's default is HTTPS, so --plain-http has to be explicit.

Follow-up: once a real pi-as-c2w image exists, replace the write-bundled-wasm step with an actual c2w build. Same oras push command works unchanged.
